me":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"le","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Lewis   or respelling of   Lou  , as borne by the impresario  Lew Grade  (  1906–98 , originally  Louis Winogradsky )."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Robert le Nae-peer was born in 1180, in Fife, Scotland, United Kingdom as the son of Alwyn MacMurdoc. He had at least 1 son with Mary Murray."},"et":{"1180–":"1180–Surnud","1180–Male":"1180–Surnud","1158–Female":"1158–Surnud","1190–1300":"1190–1300","1140–1190":"1140–1190","1190":"1190","about 1190":"umbes 1190","1158":"1158","1300":"1300","1140":"1140","1180":"1180","Scotland":"Scotland","Fife, Scotland":"Fife, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1180–":"1180–Kuollut","1180–Male":"1180–Kuollut","1158–Female":"1158–Kuollut","1190–1300":"1190–1300","1140–1190":"1140–1190","1190":"1190","about 1190":"noin 1190","1158":"1158","1300":"1300","1140":"1140","1180":"1180","Scotland":"Scotland","Fife,